## 6. Ringdown Fit

Fit performed on full post-bang data by Copilot (cold reviewer).
Fit target: J_max(t) − J_vac = A · exp(−λt)

Three models tested:

|Model      |Parameters                            |Fit quality|
|-----------|--------------------------------------|-----------|
|Exponential|A = 0.639,  λ = 8.2 × 10⁻⁶            |Best fit   |
|Power law  |A = 6.13,   β = 0.31                  |Poor       |
|Hybrid     |A = 3.82e-8, β = −1.7, λ = 3.36 × 10⁻⁵|Collapsed  |

**Result: pure exponential.**

Derived timescale:

```
τ = 1/λ = 1/(8.2 × 10⁻⁶) ≈ 1.22 × 10⁵ steps
```

This matches the observed transition point (~step 120,000–174,000)
to within measurement precision of the 2,000-step log interval.

### 6.1 Physical Interpretation of λ

The J field equation near the fixed point reduces to:

```
dJ/dt ≈ (−j_decay + j_alpha · ⟨α−1⟩_vac) · J
```

With j_decay = 0.82, j_alpha = 0.38, and dt = 0.0007:

```
λ_bare = j_decay · dt = 0.82 × 0.0007 = 5.74 × 10⁻⁴ per step
```

Observed: λ = 8.2 × 10⁻⁶ per step.

**λ_observed is ~70× slower than λ_bare.** The vacuum is not governed
by j_decay alone. The ν–J and α–J couplings are actively stabilizing J
near the fixed point, producing a much slower effective relaxation than
the bare parameter predicts.

This is evidence of **coupling-stabilized vacuum**: J_vac = 0.4019 is
not set by any single parameter. It is a fixed point of the coupled
three-field system.

