## 9. Theoretical Significance

### 9.1 Vacuum without fine-tuning

The substrate finds J_vac = 0.4019 dynamically. No parameter was set
to produce this value. It is a consequence of the coupled field equations
reaching a fixed point after a bang event. This is a direct demonstration
of the NKP claim that vacuum structure is a coherence property of the
substrate, not a background assumption.

The cosmological constant problem arises in GR and QFT because neither
framework has a mechanism to select a vacuum energy from dynamics. This
simulation demonstrates that a substrate model can produce a stable,
finite vacuum value without tuning.

### 9.2 Directionality from excitation

The winner of the bang competition (Survivor 3) was not selected by
initial conditions. It was selected by coupling structure at the moment
of threshold crossing. Before the bang, the substrate had no preferred
direction. The bang event created one. This is consistent with the NKP
theoretical claim: directionality is implied but only after an excitation
emerges.

### 9.3 Finite post-bang invariants

J_max, ν_std, and field stress all remain finite throughout the run,
including at and after the bang event. No divergence occurs. The bang
is a phase transition in window structure, not a singularity. This is
consistent with NKP Prediction 1: in regimes where GR predicts curvature
singularities, the substrate framework predicts finite coherence measures
and a transition in window structure.

